properties.description: A straightforward opening hole that allows a good start to your day with a precision short iron second shot.

A well struck tee shot is a must on this extremely difficult second hole.  The left bunkersoff the tee test a player hoping to hit the green in regulation.  The second green at Pelican Golf Club is the most challenging on the property with dramatic fall offs on all sides.

A well struck tee shot is a must on this extremely difficult second hole.  The left bunkersoff the tee test a player hoping to hit the green in regulation.  The second green at Pelican Golf Club is the most challenging on the property with dramatic fall offs on all sides.

A unique hole with no bunkers and out of bounds looming down the left.  After a solid drive,players will be left with a long second shot to a very large green.  This green complexhas a “thumbprint”, made known by golf architects C.B. Macdonald and Seth Raynor.

A soft bend left to right encourages players to aim the ball at the left bunkers.  Once the tee shot has been successfully navigated, a short iron to wedge is next.  Players must hit an exact yardage as the green is horseshoe shaped and incredibly narrow back to front.

A stunning, short par 4 with majestic oak trees down the left and numerous deep bunkers down the right.  Beau Welling refers to this green as “the river” for the strong swale in the middle.  Players must hit the correct section of the green for a reasonable birdie chance.

Pelican Golf Club’s par 5 on the front 9 requires an accurate tee shot navigating trees down the right and water and bunkers left.  One of the largest greens on property that has a significant slope from left to right.  If thehole location is front right, a player will certainly have a good look at birdie, if the hole location is tucked back left, a challenge awaits!

A brand new hole during Beau Welling’s re-design.  This picturesque par 4 has a treacherously narrow green that is both hidden and runs away from the player.  A 4 on the 8thhole at Pelican Golf Club is a great success.
A well calculated medium to short iron with provide plenty of birdie opportunities.  Players must navigate this undulating green and tucked hole locations with fear of water looming right.
A long, straight par 4 requires a substantial tee shot for a mid-length second shot.  This green is the largest on the property and features an elevated front tier.  Distance control is a must.

A beautiful par 4 that winds softly to the left.  A good drive stays right of the first bunker and short of the second.  Players will have a short iron to this relatively flat green.  A great hole for a close birdie chance.

A diabolical short par 3 12th awaits players.  Water guards the front of the putting surface and getting up-and-down from long is no guarantee.  The green has a large swale in the middle and is known as a sideways Biarritz.  Being on the proper section is crucial.

The longest par 4 the players will face.  Grip it and rip it as the fairway is generous.  Players will want to avoid the left greenside bunker with certain hole locations as this green is sloped back left to front right.

The only par 5 on the back 9 allows players a chance to reach the green in two when downwind.  A well navigated tee shot avoids the left and right bunkers.  Any score above 4 will be a disappointment.

A stunning long par 3 with a captivating bunker short right.  Players can use the ground contour to feed the ball on the green or get aggressive and fly it there.  When the hole location is back left, par is a great score!

A favorite amongst many of the members.  This beautiful par 4 has water nestled next to the green leaving for a scary second shot.  Players who bail right will be faced with a diabolical short game challenge.

Although a short hole on the scorecard, it frequently plays into the wind.  Players will be greeted with a large driving area but a shallow green front-to-back, requiring a precision second shot.  Avoiding the left bunkers off the tee is a must.

A strong finishing hole for Pelican Golf Club with the magnificent clubhouse framing the green.  A second shot with a long club to a green with water short will keep players focused until the final putt drops!
